title: nanostringr Package
text: NanoStringQC function computes several QC metrics appends annotation matrix. Care taken ensure data proper format. function returns different QC metric flags can used filter samples fail QC.
code: library(nanostringr) expOVD <- NanoStringQC(ovd.r, subset(expQC, OVD == "Yes")) expOVO <- NanoStringQC(ovo.r, subset(expQC, OVO == "Yes")) expOVCL <- NanoStringQC(ovc.r, subset(expQC, OVCL == "Yes")) expHLD <- NanoStringQC(hld.r, subset(expQC, HLD == "Yes")) expHLO <- NanoStringQC(hlo.r, subset(expQC, HLO == "Yes")) expQC <- rbind(expHLD, expOVD, expHLO, expOVO, expOVCL) expQC$cohort <- factor(   x = c(     rep("HLD", nrow(expHLD)),     rep("OVD", nrow(expOVD)),     rep("HLO", nrow(expHLO)),     rep("OVO", nrow(expOVO)),     rep("OVCL", nrow(expOVCL))   ),   levels = c("HLD", "OVD", "OVCL", "HLO", "OVO"),   labels = c("HL", "OC", "OVCL", "HLO", "OVO") )

title: nanostringr Package
text: HKnorm function simple normalization log transformed (base 2) gene expression data data housekeeping genes. done subtracting average log housekeeping gene expression level expression level every gene sample. example, check QC metrics Hodgkin Lymphoma data normalize housekeeping genes: can check see samples failed QC metrics [1] TRUE [1] “HL1_3” “HL1_13” “HL1_17” “HL1_18” “HL2_3” Since matched samples must remove pairs annotation data frame gene expression data frame. now normalize resulting gene expression data
code: expHLD0 <- expHLD any(expHLD0$QCFlag == "Failed") expHLD0$sampleID[which(expHLD0$QCFlag == "Failed")] expHLD <- dplyr::filter(expHLD0, sampleID != "HL1_18" & sampleID != "HL2_18") hld <- hld.r[, !colnames(hld.r) %in% c("HL1_18", "HL2_18")] # If data already log normalized hld.n <- HKnorm(hld, is.logged = TRUE)  # Otherwise, normalize to HK  hld.n <- HKnorm(hld) hld1 <- hld.n[, grep("HL1", colnames(hld.n))] exp.hld1 <- subset(expHLD, geneRLF == "HL1")  hld2 <- hld.n[, grep("HL2", colnames(hld.n))] exp.hld2 <- subset(expHLD, geneRLF == "HL2")

title: nanostringr Package
text: function batch adjustment using reference-based strategy. work HL data: can check result selecting random gene plotting expression values CodeSets
code: r <- 3 # The number of references to use choice.refs <- exp.hld1$sampleID[sample((1:dim(exp.hld1)[1]), r, replace = F)] # select reference samples randomly R1 <- t(hld1[, choice.refs]) R2 <- t(hld2[, paste("HL2", getNum(choice.refs), sep = "_")]) Y <- t(hld2[, !colnames(hld2) %in% paste("HL2", getNum(choice.refs), sep = "_")]) S2.r <- t(refMethod(Y, R1, R2)) # Data from CodeSet 2 now calibrated for CodeSet 1 set.seed(2016) gene <- sample(1:nrow(hld1), 1) par(mfrow = c(1, 2)) plot(t(hld1[gene, ]), t(hld2[gene, ]), xlab = "HL1", ylab = "HL2",      main = "No Correction") abline(0, 1)  plot(t(hld1[gene, !(colnames(hld1) %in% choice.refs)]), t(S2.r[gene, ]),      xlab = "HL1", ylab = "HL2", main = "Corrected") abline(0, 1)

text: Provides quality control (QC), normalization, batch effect correction operations 'NanoString nCounter' data, Talhouk et al. (2016) doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0153844 . Various metrics used determine samples passed failed QC. Gene expression first normalized housekeeping genes, reference-based approach used adjust batch effects. Raw NanoString data can imported form Reporter Code Count (RCC) files.

title: Read NanoString RCC files — rcc
text: read_rcc() reads directory RCC files outputs list two elements: raw: tibble parsed counts multiple RCC files created calling parse_counts() sample. Columns include "Code.Class", "Name", "Accession", column sample ID. one row per gene. exp: tibble parsed attributes multiple RCC files created calling parse_attributes() sample. Columns include "File.Name" (sample ID), "geneRLF", "nanostring.date", "cartridgeID", "lane.number", fov.count", "fov.counted", "binding.density". one row per sample. parse_counts() reads single RCC file returns tibble parsed counts. parse_attributes() reads single RCC file returns list parsed attributes.

title: Read NanoString RCC files — rcc
text: RCC files sample direct outputs NanoString runs. can extract counts gene sample. Sample attributes include sample ID, GeneRLF, date, cartridge ID, lane number, Fov count, Fov counted, binding density. read_rcc() merges count attribute data across samples. path points zipped RCC file multiple samples, zip file uncompressed directory RCC sample files created name. file extensions ".RCC" ".rcc" allowed.
